<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Active Listening Mode
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        The Event Point becomes active once the trigger condition is met and remains active as a valid dependency target for the rest of the mission.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What Active Listening Mode Does
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Active</Bold> is the safest default listening mode for most authored mission chains. When
        the trigger condition is met, the Event Point becomes active and stays active permanently (or
        until explicitly killed by other logic). This makes it a reliable dependency target for later
        mission Event Points.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Once active, the Event Point remains active even if the trigger condition later becomes false.
        For example, a <Bold>Radius</Bold> trigger with <Bold>Active</Bold> listening mode fires when
        the player enters the radius and stays active even after the player leaves.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Practical meaning:</Run>
                <Run> Use Active for Event Points that should fire once and then remain available for other Event Points to depend on. This is the standard choice for most objectives, checkpoints, and mission progress markers.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        When To Use Active
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Active</Bold> when the Event Point should fire once and then remain available for other
        Event Points to depend on. This is appropriate for:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,8">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Mission objectives</Bold> - The objective completes once and stays complete</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Checkpoints</Bold> - The checkpoint is reached and stays reached</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Scripted events</Bold> - The event fires once and later logic depends on it having fired</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>State changes</Bold> - A group spawns, a door opens, an NPC appears — the change is permanent</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Dependency sources</Bold> - Other Event Points will depend on this one firing</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Behavior
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        When the trigger condition becomes true, the Event Point fires and becomes active. It remains
        active even if the trigger condition later becomes false. The Event Point stays active for the
        rest of the mission unless explicitly killed by Kill Waypoint or similar logic.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        <Bold>Example:</Bold> A Message Event Point with <Bold>Radius</Bold> trigger and <Bold>Active</Bold>
        listening mode:
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="40,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Player enters the radius</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Event Point fires, message appears, Event Point becomes active</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Player leaves the radius</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Event Point stays active (message stays visible)</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Later Event Points can depend on this Event Point and they will fire because it's still active</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Patterns
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Conversation With Dependency Chain
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A Conversation Event Point with <Bold>Person Used</Bold> trigger and <Bold>Active</Bold> listening
        mode starts when the player talks to an NPC. It stays active after the conversation starts, allowing
        later Event Points to use <Bold>Conversation Over</Bold> or <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on it.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Checkpoint Marker
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A Message Event Point with <Bold>Radius</Bold> trigger and <Bold>Active</Bold> listening mode
        shows an objective message when the player enters an area. The message remains visible (and the
        Event Point remains active) even after the player leaves, marking the checkpoint as permanently
        reached.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Enemy Wave Spawn
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A Group Life Event Point with <Bold>Dependency</Bold> trigger and <Bold>Active</Bold> listening
        mode spawns enemy reinforcements when a previous objective completes. The group stays alive (and
        the Event Point stays active) for the rest of the mission.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Mission-Start Setup
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Most Event Points with <Bold>None</Bold> trigger use <Bold>Active</Bold> listening mode. They
        become active at mission start and stay active. This includes player spawn points, ambient NPCs,
        placed vehicles, and default mission setup.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Retail Examples
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The vast majority of Event Points in retail missions use <Bold>Active</Bold> listening mode. This
        includes nearly all Message, Nav Beacon, Conversation, Create NPC, Create Vehicle, and objective-related
        Event Points. It is the default choice and the safest option for mission authoring.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Comparison With Other Listening Modes
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Active vs Active While</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        <Bold>Active</Bold> stays active permanently once triggered. <Bold>Active While</Bold> is active
        only while the trigger condition remains true. Use <Bold>Active</Bold> when you want permanent
        progress markers. Use <Bold>Active While</Bold> when you want temporary states that should deactivate
        when the condition stops.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Active vs Active Die</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        <Bold>Active</Bold> stays active and can be depended on by later Event Points. <Bold>Active Die</Bold>
        fires once and immediately becomes inactive/dead. Use <Bold>Active</Bold> for dependency chains.
        Use <Bold>Active Die</Bold> for one-shot cleanup actions that should not be dependency targets.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Active vs Active Time</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        <Bold>Active</Bold> stays active permanently. <Bold>Active Time</Bold> stays active for a limited
        duration controlled by the After Timer field. Use <Bold>Active</Bold> for permanent changes. Use
        <Bold>Active Time</Bold> for temporary effects that should automatically end.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Basic Active Listening Mode Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Identify the Event Point that should fire once and stay active</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Choose the appropriate trigger type (None, Dependency, Radius, etc.)</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set Listening Mode to <Bold>Active</Bold></Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Configure trigger-specific fields (EP Ref, Radius, etc.)</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test that the Event Point fires when the trigger condition is met</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Verify that the Event Point stays active after firing (check dependency chains work)</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the Event Point does not fire repeatedly if the trigger condition happens again</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Authoring tip:</Run>
                <Run> Active is the safest default for most Event Points. Use it unless you specifically need Active While (continuous state), Active Time (timed effect), or Active Die (one-shot cleanup).</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>
